{"add":{"doc":{"id":"84aa40965bb6abcd8ce1e7f8999023d19c0eb2e9e82b3e4194ff494a55d1be5b","url":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/6/68/Genc_Kalemler.jpg/130px-Genc_Kalemler.jpg","previous":[],"after":["In 1908, Sultan Abdülhamid II had instituted a constitutional government, and the parliament subsequently elected was composed almost entirely of members of the Committee of Union and Progress (also known as the \"Young Turks\"). The Young Turks (ژون تورکلر Jön Türkler) had opposed themselves to the increasingly authoritarian Ottoman government, and soon came to identify themselves with a specifically Turkish national identity. Along with this notion developed the idea of a Turkish and even pan-Turkish nation (Turkish: millet), and so the literature of this period came to be known as \"National Literature\" (Turkish: millî edebiyyât). It was during this period that the Persian- and Arabic-inflected Ottoman Turkish language was definitively turned away from as a vehicle for written literature, and that literature began to assert itself as being specifically Turkish, rather than Ottoman."]}}}